<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,327,1156]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,320,367,393]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. A single whorl of setae on flagellomeres, maxillary palpus large, cardo–stipes mesally fused. Distal end of postmentum projected between the labella. Pronotal apodeme curved, katepisternum bare ventrally. No incomplete false r–m vein on M 
<number box="[644,652,464,478]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="1.0">1</number>
. No pretergites 
<number box="[841,857,448,474]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
, sternites 
<number box="[975,1019,448,474]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
unsclerotized. Male sternite 
<number box="[1358,1373,448,474]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="7.0">7</number>
trapezoid, with a posterior mesal incision and a pair of lateral projection and a differentiated ventral projection. Aedeagal plate absent, aedeagus opening at the end of a long, coiled projection; tergite 
<number box="[1166,1181,530,556]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="9.0">9</number>
laterally compressed, straight dorsally and rounded distally (
<figureCitation box="[603,732,570,596]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 16" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[200,1398,197,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[200,1398,194,1935]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 16. Male terminalia of Swammerdamellini genera. 8 – 10. Abrhexosa panamensis (Cook). Male holotype (8, ventral; 9, lateral, 10, dorsal). 11 – 13. Quateiella sp. 1 (11, ventral; 12, lateral, 13, dorsal). 14 – 16. Cooka similis (Beekey). Male paratype (14, ventral; 15, lateral, 16, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/179670/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
Figs. 
<number box="[669,732,570,596]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="9.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="8.0">8–10</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,327,1156]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,330,610,636]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Discussion</emphasis>
. This genus was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Freeman" box="[702,897,610,636]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" refString="Freeman, P. (1990) Redescription of seven Oriental species of Scatopsidae (Diptera) described by F. W. Edwards in the genus Scatopse. Entomologists' Monthly Magazine, 126, 9 - 19." type="journal article" year="1990">
Freeman (
<number box="[828,889,610,636]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="1990.0">1990</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for a single Oriental species described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Edwards" box="[151,342,650,676]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" refString="Edwards, F. W. (1928) Diptera Nematocera from the Federated Malay States Museum. Journal of the federated Malay States Museum, 14, 1 - 139." type="journal article" year="1928">
Edwards (
<number box="[269,333,650,676]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="1928.0">1928</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. In the original description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Freeman (1990)" authorityName="Freeman" authorityYear="1990" box="[694,1013,650,676]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Abrhexosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[694,819,651,676]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Abrhexosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Freeman" box="[826,1013,650,676]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" refString="Freeman, P. (1990) Redescription of seven Oriental species of Scatopsidae (Diptera) described by F. W. Edwards in the genus Scatopse. Entomologists' Monthly Magazine, 126, 9 - 19." type="journal article" year="1990">
Freeman (
<number box="[943,1004,650,676]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="1990.0">1990</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
already called attention for the similarities shared by that species with 
<taxonomicName box="[567,667,691,716]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Rhexoza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[567,667,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Rhexoza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[723,861,691,716]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Akorhexoza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[723,861,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Akorhexoza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially the shape of the maxillary palpus and the unsclerotized abdominal sternites 
<number box="[592,640,730,756]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Freeman" box="[651,841,730,756]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" refString="Freeman, P. (1990) Redescription of seven Oriental species of Scatopsidae (Diptera) described by F. W. Edwards in the genus Scatopse. Entomologists' Monthly Magazine, 126, 9 - 19." type="journal article" year="1990">
Freeman (
<number box="[769,832,730,756]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="1990.0">1990</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, however, noted that the reduction in the extension of the radial sector of the wing, the shape of the female sternite 
<number box="[943,958,770,796]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="8.0">8</number>
and of the male gonocoxites would be enough to justify a separated genus for the 
<typeStatus box="[674,726,810,836]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">type</typeStatus>
–species. Actually, some of the Nearctic species previously included in 
<taxonomicName box="[291,391,851,876]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Rhexoza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[291,391,851,876]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Rhexoza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Neotropical species 
<taxonomicName box="[732,904,851,876]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Abrhexosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="panamensis">
<emphasis box="[732,904,851,876]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">R. panamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fit in 
<taxonomicName box="[978,1102,851,876]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Abrhexosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[978,1102,851,876]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Abrhexosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, since they share these apomorphic features. The male terminalia of all these species do not present an aedeagal plate and the aedeagus opening is at the end of a long, usually coiled tube. Parameres are also elongated and rather compressed distally (
<bibRefCitation author="Amorim" box="[219,399,970,996]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" refString="Amorim, D. S. (1982) Sistematica filogenetica dos Scatopsidae. Masters Thesis, Universidade de Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo. v + 173 pp + 74 pl." type="book" year="1982">
Amorim, 
<number box="[336,399,970,996]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). These features seem to be synapomorphic for the genus and allow some confidence in their inclusion with the 
<typeStatus box="[429,479,1010,1036]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">type</typeStatus>
–species in 
<taxonomicName box="[616,741,1011,1036]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Abrhexosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[616,741,1011,1036]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Abrhexosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
